<section xml:id="sec-solving-systems-of-linear-equations-by-graphing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Solving Systems of Linear Equations by Graphing</title>

  <p> Since a solution of a system of equations is common to both equations, it is also a point common to the graphs of both equations. To find the solution of a system of two linear equations, we graph the equations and see where the lines intersect. </p>
<example>
  <p> Solve the system of equations by graphing
    <me>
      \begin{cases}
          2 x - y \amp = 6 \\
          x + 3 y \amp =10. 
        \end{cases}
    </me>   
      We can graph a linear equation by finding two ordered pair solutions or solving the equation for <m>y</m> and using the <m>y-</m>intercept and the slope. </p>
  <p>As the method of graphing is often our choice, I personally like solving for <m>y</m> and using the <m>y-</m>intercept and the slope, especially when the <m>y-</m>intercept is an integer. </p>
  <p>To verify if the <m>y-</m>intercept is an integer, check if the constant on the right side of the equation is a multiple (divisible) of the coefficient of <m>y</m>.</p>
  <p> In the first equation, <m>2x-y=6</m>, the constant on the right side, <m>6</m>, is divisible by the coefficient of <m>y</m>, <m>-1</m>, indicating that the y-intercept will be an integer. In contrast, in the second equation, <m>x+3y=10</m>, the y-intercept will not be an integer since the constant on the right side, <m>10</m>, is not divisible by the coefficient of <m>y</m>, <m>3</m>.</p>
  <p>Thus, to graph the first line, I will solve the equation for , <m>y</m>, while for the second, I will calculate two ordered pair solutions (make a <m>t-</m>table).
  To solve the first equation for <m>y</m>, move the <m>x-</m>term to the right (flip the sign) and divide out the coefficient of <m>y:</m></p>
    <md>
      <mrow> 2 x - y \amp= 6 </mrow>
      <mrow>- y \amp= - 2 x + 6</mrow>
      <mrow>y \amp= 2 x - 6 </mrow>
    </md>
  <p>It is now in the slope-intercept form. To graph it, we start by plotting the <m>y-</m>intercept, <m>(0,-6)</m>,  and then find the additional point(s) using the slope <m>m = 2 = 2/1</m> (rise over run, two units up, one to the right).</p>

      <figure xml:id="systems-of-equations-graphing-unique-first-line">
