  <p>To graph the second equation, I will find two ordered pairs by plugging a random value for <m>x</m> or <m>y</m> and solving for the remaining variable. While no rule favors one variable over the other for which we plug the values, checking the coefficients is helpful. If one of the variables in the equation has a coefficient of <m>1</m> or <m>- 1</m>, it becomes easier to solve for that variable. Thus, I would plug the values for the other variable and solve for the “easy one.” </p>

  <p>In our second equation, <m>x+3y=10</m>, the coefficient of <m>x</m> is <m>1</m>. Therefore, I'll calculate two ordered pairs by substituting values for <m>y</m> and solving for <m>x</m>.</p> 

  <p>Quick reminder: I choose values to <m>y</m> at random. Once I calculate the <m>x-</m> vales, I will record the solutions in the form of a <m>t-</m>table, and moving forward, I will refer to this approach as the <m>t-</m>table method.</p>

